recordings.rmk:
Recorded:

  • chutter call, tit tit churrrr , at e.g. 0:01.1 and 0:10.5
  • chutter call, drrrrt , at e.g. 0:02.6 and 0:12.9
  • call, short tsee notes , at e.g. 0:04.9 and 0:23.7
  • (alarm) call, seeee seeeee , at e.g. 0:08.2

General observations: Coniferous forest next to a yard and some fields. Two tits foraging in a couple of Scots pines. Clear skies. 5 decimeters of snow. Temperature: -14°C/6.8°F. Westerly wind, light breeze.

Recording remarks: The tsee call is according to NatureGuides (2020) used at close range given by birds foraging within 10 metres of one another. The seeee call is referred to as a hawk alarm-call.

Other distinguishable species:

  • Eurasian Bullfinch, Pyrrhula pyrrhula, call, phü, at 0:15.9 (vaguely)
  • Willow Tit, Poecile montanus, call, tchãã, at e.g. 0:20.7
  • Great Spotted Woodpecker Dendrocopos major, foraging, at 0:26.8 (very vaguely)

Sound classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore.

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Olympus LS-P4 recorder.

recordings.loc: Ireland (near  Bangor), Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk: In the course of trying to record a Robin singing in pre-dawn darkness (at 0630hrs) I disturbed a Blue Tit. The bird approached me on the far side of a thick hedge and 'sang'.  This is actually not as bizarre as it sounds - Blue Tits (exclusively males?) quite often use song as a vocalisation that seems connected with relieving stress - or drawing attention to a situation they find stressful. Such as a human night prowler!  After several pure 'song salvos' the bird retreats and, as it does so, you can hear its more typical 'narky' alarm signature at 0:22.
